Boat Stability & Buoyancy Calculation

Estimated total mass of the boat system:

Boat mass ≈ 400–500 g
Average mass used for calculation ≈ 0.45 kg

According to Archimedes’ Principle, the buoyant force equals the weight of the displaced water.

Density of water:

ρ = 1000 kg/m³

Required displaced volume:

V = mass / density
V = 0.45 / 1000
V = 0.00045 m³

Convert cubic meters to liters:

1 m³ = 1000 L

0.00045 × 1000 = 0.45 L

Required displacement ≈ 0.45 liters

This means the boat must displace about 450 mL of water to float, which is easily achieved using a thermocol hull due to its very low density.

Motor RPM Calculation

Motor specification:

Motor KV = 930 KV

KV means RPM per volt.

Motor RPM is calculated as:

RPM = KV × Voltage

Using a 3S LiPo battery (11.1V)

RPM = 930 × 11.1
RPM ≈ 10,323 RPM

So the motor spins at roughly 10k RPM under no load.

Boat Speed Estimation

Assuming a small DIY propeller pitch of about 4 cm per revolution.

Convert pitch to meters:

4 cm = 0.04 m

Distance moved per revolution = 0.04 m

Speed formula:

Speed = (RPM × pitch) / 60

Speed = (10323 × 0.04) / 60
Speed = 412.92 / 60
Speed ≈ 6.88 m/s

Convert to km/h:

1 m/s = 3.6 km/h

6.88 × 3.6 ≈ 24.7 km/h

Theoretical speed ≈ 25 km/h

Due to drag, propeller inefficiency, and water resistance, the practical speed is usually 50–70% of theoretical speed.

Estimated real-world speed:

≈ 12–18 km/h
